    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This 5-page paper proposes that quantum field theory allows a particle to tunnel out of a non-singular black hole from deep inside \u2014 crossing both an inner and an outer horizon \u2014 with a probability that is suppressed polynomially rather than exponentially. The review board found the core physical idea interesting but identified a potentially fatal flaw in the mathematical construction underlying all numerical results: the global coordinate used to do the calculation may fold distinct parts of the spacetime onto the same coordinate values, making the apparent tunneling amplitude a mathematical artifact rather than a physical effect. A third reviewer disputed this diagnosis. Even setting that dispute aside, the connection between the computed quantity and a genuine particle escape mechanism is not firmly established, and the speculation about information loss and 4D black holes goes well beyond what the calculation supports.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper exploits 2D conformal invariance to reduce QFT on a Painlev\u00e9\u2013Gullstrand non-singular black hole (inner horizon at r_i, outer at r_o) to flat-space QFT in a globally constructed null coordinate (\u0169, v). The Hegerfeldt-type one-particle transition amplitude between localized states in causally disconnected inner and outer regions is then computed from the flat-space propagator. The paper claims an asymptotic integrated tunneling probability P_out \u2192 W/[4\u03c0\u00b2(\u03ba_i\u207b\u00b9 + \u03ba_o\u207b\u00b9)]. Two reviewers (claude, gemini) concluded that \u0169 equals zero at both horizons and is positive in both the outer and inner regions, making the coordinate map non-injective \u2014 a formally fatal defect that would cause the small \u0394\u0169 driving the large transition amplitude to be a coordinate artifact rather than physical proximity. A third reviewer (codex) disputed this, reading eq. (6) as assigning strictly disjoint \u0169-ranges to the three regions. All reviewers agreed independently that the vacuum state is not physically identified, the Hegerfeldt amplitude does not by itself establish a dynamical escape channel, and the 4D rate estimate (eq. 26) is not derived from the model."
    }
